<p><b>Game theory</b> is the study of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Mathematical_model" title=3D"Mathematical model">mathematical models</a=
> of strategic interactions.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Myerson_1-0" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-Myerso=
n-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup> It has applications in many fields of <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Social_science" title=3D"Social science">social science=
</a>, and is used extensively in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/E=
conomics" title=3D"Economics">economics</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Logic" title=3D"Logic">logic</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Systems_science" title=3D"Systems science">systems science</a> a=
nd <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_science" title=3D"Comp=
uter science">computer science</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-2" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-2"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup> Initially, game theory addressed two-person <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Zero-sum_game" title=3D"Zero-sum game">zero-sum games</a>, i=
n which a participant's gains or losses are exactly balanced by the losses =
and gains of the other participant. In the 1950s, it was extended to the st=
udy of non zero-sum games, and was eventually applied to a wide range of <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_behavior" title=3D"Human behav=
ior">behavioral relations</a>. It is now an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Umbrella_term" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Umbrella term">umbr=
ella term</a> for the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Science" tit=
le=3D"Science">science</a> of rational <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Decision-making" title=3D"Decision-making">decision making</a> in huma=
ns, animals, and computers.
</p><p>Modern game theory began with the idea of <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Mixed_Strategy_Equilibria" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Mi=
xed Strategy Equilibria">mixed-strategy equilibria</a> in two-person zero-s=
um games and its proof by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_von=
_Neumann" title=3D"John von Neumann">John von Neumann</a>. Von Neumann's or=
iginal proof used the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brouwer_fixe=
d-point_theorem" title=3D"Brouwer fixed-point theorem">Brouwer fixed-point =
theorem</a> on continuous mappings into compact <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Convex_set" title=3D"Convex set">convex sets</a>, which becam=
e a standard method in game theory and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Mathematical_economics" title=3D"Mathematical economics">mathematical =
economics</a>. His paper was followed by <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Theory_of_Games_and_Economic_Behavior" title=3D"Theory of Games a=
nd Economic Behavior">Theory of Games and Economic Behavior</a></i> (1944),=
 co-written with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oskar_Morgenstern=
" title=3D"Oskar Morgenstern">Oskar Morgenstern</a>, which considered <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cooperative_game_theory" title=3D"Coope=
rative game theory">cooperative games</a> of several players.<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_=
theory#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The second edition provided an <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Von_Neumann%E2%80%93Morgenstern_utility_theorem=
" title=3D"Von Neumann=E2=80=93Morgenstern utility theorem">axiomatic theor=
y</a> of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Expected_utility_hypothes=
is" title=3D"Expected utility hypothesis">expected utility</a>, which allow=
ed mathematical statisticians and economists to treat decision-making under=
 uncertainty.
</p><p>Game theory was developed extensively in the 1950s, and was explicit=
ly applied to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Evolution" title=3D"=
Evolution">evolution</a> in the 1970s, although similar developments go bac=
k at least as far as the 1930s. Game theory has been widely recognized as a=
n important tool in many fields. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J=
ohn_Maynard_Smith" title=3D"John Maynard Smith">John Maynard Smith</a> was =
awarded the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crafoord_Prize" title=
=3D"Crafoord Prize">Crafoord Prize</a> for his application of <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Evolutionary_game_theory" title=3D"Evolutionary=
 game theory">evolutionary game theory</a> in 1999, and fifteen game theori=
sts have won the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nobel_Memorial_Pr=
ize_in_Economic_Sciences" title=3D"Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Science=
s">Nobel Prize in economics</a> as of 2020, including most recently <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Milgrom" title=3D"Paul Milgrom">Paul=
 Milgrom</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_B._Wilson"=
 title=3D"Robert B. Wilson">Robert B. Wilson</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"toclimit-3"><meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc"></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DGame_theory&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>edit</span><=
/a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Discussions on the mathematics of games began long before the rise of mo=
dern, mathematical game theory. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ge=
rolamo_Cardano" title=3D"Gerolamo Cardano">Cardano</a> wrote on games of ch=
ance in <i>Liber de ludo aleae</i> (<i>Book on Games of Chance</i>), writte=
n around 1564 but published posthumously in 1663.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_=
note-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup> Influenced by the work of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Pierre_de_Fermat" title=3D"Pierre de Fermat">Fermat</a> and <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blaise_Pascal" title=3D"Blaise Pascal"=
>Pascal</a> on the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Problem_of_poin=
ts" title=3D"Problem of points">problem of points</a>, <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Christiaan_Huygens" title=3D"Christiaan Huygens">Huyge=
ns</a> developed the concept of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ex=
pected_value" title=3D"Expected value">expectation</a> on reasoning about t=
he structure of games of chance, publishing his gambling calculus in <i>De =
ratiociniis in ludo ale=C3=A6</i> (<i>On Reasoning in Games of Chance</i>) =
in 1657.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In 1713, a letter attributed to Charles Waldegrave, an active <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jacobitism" title=3D"Jacobitism">Jacobit=
e</a> and uncle to British diplomat <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/James_Waldegrave,_1st_Earl_Waldegrave" title=3D"James Waldegrave, 1st Ear=
l Waldegrave">James Waldegrave</a>, analyzed a game called "<a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Le_her" title=3D"Le her">le her</a>". Waldegrave =
provided a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minimax" title=3D"Minim=
ax">minimax</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mixed_strategy" cl=
ass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Mixed strategy">mixed strategy</a> solution to=
 a two-person version of the card game, and the problem is now known as the=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Waldegrave_problem" title=3D"Wald=
egrave problem">Waldegrave problem</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-GT-PD-01_6-0" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite=
_note-GT-PD-01-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-7"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In 1838, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antoine_Augustin_C=
ournot" title=3D"Antoine Augustin Cournot">Antoine Augustin Cournot</a> pro=
vided a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cournot_competition" title=
=3D"Cournot competition">model of competition</a> in <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Oligopoly" title=3D"Oligopoly">oligopolies</a>. Though h=
e did not refer to it as such, he presented a solution that is the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nash_equilibrium" title=3D"Nash equilibri=
um">Nash equilibrium</a> of the game in his <span title=3D"French-language =
text"><i lang=3D"fr">Recherches sur les principes math=C3=A9matiques de la =
th=C3=A9orie des richesses</i></span> (<i>Researches into the Mathematical =
Principles of the Theory of Wealth</i>). In 1883, <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Joseph_Bertrand" title=3D"Joseph Bertrand">Joseph Bertrand<=
/a> critiqued Cournot's model as unrealistic, providing an alternative mode=
l of price competition<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:42_8-0" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-:42-8"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> which would later be formalized by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Francis_Ysidro_Edgeworth" title=3D"Francis Ysidro Edgeworth">Francis Ysi=
dro Edgeworth</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-9" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-9"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In 1913, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ernst_Zermelo" tit=
le=3D"Ernst Zermelo">Ernst Zermelo</a> published <span title=3D"German-lang=
uage text"><i lang=3D"de">=C3=9Cber eine Anwendung der Mengenlehre auf die =
Theorie des Schachspiels</i></span> (<i>On an Application of Set Theory to =
the Theory of the Game of Chess</i>), which proved that the optimal chess s=
trategy is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Strictly_determined_gam=
e" title=3D"Strictly determined game">strictly determined</a>.<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-10" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gam=
e_theory#cite_note-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Foundation">Foundation</h3>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DGame_theory&amp;=
action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Foundation"><span>edi=
t</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:JohnvonNeumann-LosAlamos.gif" class=3D"mw-fil=
e-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/t=
humb/5/5e/JohnvonNeumann-LosAlamos.gif/250px-JohnvonNeumann-LosAlamos.gif" =
decoding=3D"async" width=3D"190" height=3D"248" class=3D"mw-file-element" d=
ata-file-width=3D"490" data-file-height=3D"639"></a><figcaption><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_von_Neumann" title=3D"John von Neumann">=
John von Neumann</a></figcaption></figure>
<p>The work of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_von_Neumann" t=
itle=3D"John von Neumann">John von Neumann</a> established game theory as i=
ts own independent field in the early-to-mid 20th century, with von Neumann=
 publishing his paper <i>On the Theory of Games of Strategy</i> in 1928.<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-11" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_no=
te-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup> Von Neumann's original proof used <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Brouwer%27s_fixed-point_theorem" class=3D"mw-redirect" t=
itle=3D"Brouwer's fixed-point theorem">Brouwer's fixed-point theorem</a> on=
 continuous <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Map_(mathematics)" tit=
le=3D"Map (mathematics)">mappings</a> into compact <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Convex_set" title=3D"Convex set">convex sets</a>, which be=
came a standard method in game theory and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Mathematical_economics" title=3D"Mathematical economics">mathematic=
al economics</a>. Von Neumann's work in game theory culminated in his 1944 =
book <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Theory_of_Games_and_Econom=
ic_Behavior" title=3D"Theory of Games and Economic Behavior">Theory of Game=
s and Economic Behavior</a></i>, co-authored with <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Oskar_Morgenstern" title=3D"Oskar Morgenstern">Oskar Morgen=
stern</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-13" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The second editio=
n of this book provided an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Axiomat=
ic_set_theory" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Axiomatic set theory">axiomat=
ic theory of utility</a>, which reincarnated <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Daniel_Bernoulli" title=3D"Daniel Bernoulli">Daniel Bernoulli's<=
/a> old theory of utility (of money) as an independent discipline. This fou=
ndational work contains the method for finding mutually consistent solution=
s for two-person zero-sum games. Subsequent work focused primarily on <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cooperative_game_theory" title=3D"Coope=
rative game theory">cooperative game</a> theory, which analyzes optimal str=
ategies for groups of individuals, presuming that they can enforce agreemen=
ts between them about proper strategies.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-14" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-14"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup>
</p><p>In his 1938 book <span title=3D"French-language text"><i lang=3D"fr"=
>Applications aux Jeux de Hasard</i></span> and earlier notes, <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89mile_Borel" title=3D"=C3=89mile Borel">=
=C3=89mile Borel</a> proved a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mini=
max_theorem" title=3D"Minimax theorem">minimax theorem</a> for two-person z=
ero-sum matrix games only when the pay-off matrix is symmetric and provided=
 a solution to a non-trivial infinite game (known in English as <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blotto_game" title=3D"Blotto game">Blotto gam=
e</a>). Borel conjectured the non-existence of mixed-strategy equilibria in=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Finite_Game" class=3D"mw-redirect=
" title=3D"Finite Game">finite two-person zero-sum games</a>, a conjecture =
that was proved false by von Neumann.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-15" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-15"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup>
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:John_f_nash_20061102_3.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-=
description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thu=
mb/9/91/John_f_nash_20061102_3.jpg/250px-John_f_nash_20061102_3.jpg" decodi=
ng=3D"async" width=3D"190" height=3D"239" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-fi=
le-width=3D"715" data-file-height=3D"901"></a><figcaption><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Forbes_Nash_Jr." title=3D"John Forbes Nash Jr.=
">John Nash</a></figcaption></figure>
<p>In 1950, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Forbes_Nash" clas=
s=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"John Forbes Nash">John Nash</a> developed a crit=
erion for mutual consistency of players' strategies known as the <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nash_equilibrium" title=3D"Nash equilibrium"=
>Nash equilibrium</a>, applicable to a wider variety of games than the crit=
erion proposed by von Neumann and Morgenstern. Nash proved that every finit=
e n-player, non-zero-sum (not just two-player zero-sum) <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Non-cooperative_game" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"=
Non-cooperative game">non-cooperative game</a> has what is now known as a N=
ash equilibrium in mixed strategies.
</p><p>Game theory experienced a flurry of activity in the 1950s, during wh=
ich the concepts of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Core_(econ=
omics)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Core (economics)">core</a>, the <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Extensive_form_game" class=3D"mw-redir=
ect" title=3D"Extensive form game">extensive form game</a>, <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fictitious_play" title=3D"Fictitious play">fictit=
ious play</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Repeated_game" titl=
e=3D"Repeated game">repeated games</a>, and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Shapley_value" title=3D"Shapley value">Shapley value</a> were=
 developed. The 1950s also saw the first applications of game theory to <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philosophy" title=3D"Philosophy">phil=
osophy</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Political_science" =
title=3D"Political science">political science</a>. The first mathematical d=
iscussion of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prisoner%27s_dile=
mma" title=3D"Prisoner's dilemma">prisoner's dilemma</a> appeared, and an e=
xperiment was undertaken by mathematicians <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Merrill_M._Flood" title=3D"Merrill M. Flood">Merrill M. Flood</a> =
and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Melvin_Dresher" title=3D"Melvi=
n Dresher">Melvin Dresher</a>, as part of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/RAND_Corporation" title=3D"RAND Corporation">RAND Corporation</=
a>'s investigations into game theory. RAND pursued the studies because of p=
ossible applications to global <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nuc=
lear_strategy" title=3D"Nuclear strategy">nuclear strategy</a>.<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-stanfordprisoner_16-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-stanfordprisoner-16"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Prize-winning_achievements"=
>Prize-winning achievements</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/i=
ndex.php?title=3DGame_theory&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Ed=
it section: Prize-winning achievements"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D=
"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In 1965, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reinhard_Selten" title=
=3D"Reinhard Selten">Reinhard Selten</a> introduced his <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Solution_concept" title=3D"Solution concept">solution=
 concept</a> of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Subgame_perfect_eq=
uilibrium" title=3D"Subgame perfect equilibrium">subgame perfect equilibria=
</a>, which further refined the Nash equilibrium. Later he would introduce =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trembling_hand_perfection" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Trembling hand perfection">trembling hand perfect=
ion</a> as well. In 1994 Nash, Selten and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/John_Harsanyi" title=3D"John Harsanyi">Harsanyi</a> became <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nobel_Memorial_Prize_in_Economic_Sciences=
" title=3D"Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences">Economics Nobel Laure=
ates</a> for their contributions to economic game theory.
</p><p>In the 1970s, game theory was extensively applied in <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biology" title=3D"Biology">biology</a>, largely a=
s a result of the work of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_May=
nard_Smith" title=3D"John Maynard Smith">John Maynard Smith</a> and his <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Evolutionarily_stable_strategy" title=
=3D"Evolutionarily stable strategy">evolutionarily stable strategy</a>. In =
addition, the concepts of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Correlat=
ed_equilibrium" title=3D"Correlated equilibrium">correlated equilibrium</a>=
, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trembling_hand_perfect_equilibri=
um" title=3D"Trembling hand perfect equilibrium">trembling hand perfection<=
/a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Common_knowledge_(logic)" =
title=3D"Common knowledge (logic)">common knowledge</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
17" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theor=
y#cite_note-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>a<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup> were introduced and analyzed.
</p><p>In 1994, John Nash was awarded the Nobel Memorial Prize in the Econo=
mic Sciences for his contribution to game theory. Nash's most famous contri=
bution to game theory is the concept of the Nash equilibrium, which is a so=
lution concept for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Non-cooperative=
_game_theory" title=3D"Non-cooperative game theory">non-cooperative games</=
a>, published in 1951. A Nash equilibrium is a set of strategies, one for e=
ach player, such that no player can improve their payoff by unilaterally ch=
anging their strategy.
</p><p>In 2005, game theorists <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tho=
mas_Schelling" title=3D"Thomas Schelling">Thomas Schelling</a> and <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_Aumann" title=3D"Robert Aumann">Ro=
bert Aumann</a> followed Nash, Selten, and Harsanyi as Nobel Laureates. Sch=
elling worked on dynamic models, early examples of <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Evolutionary_game_theory" title=3D"Evolutionary game theor=
y">evolutionary game theory</a>. Aumann contributed more to the equilibrium=
 school, introducing equilibrium coarsening and correlated equilibria, and =
developing an extensive formal analysis of the assumption of common knowled=
ge and of its consequences.
</p><p>In 2007, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leonid_Hurwicz" ti=
tle=3D"Leonid Hurwicz">Leonid Hurwicz</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Eric_Maskin" title=3D"Eric Maskin">Eric Maskin</a>, and <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roger_Myerson" title=3D"Roger Myerson">Roger=
 Myerson</a> were awarded the Nobel Prize in Economics "for having laid the=
 foundations of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mechanism_design" =
title=3D"Mechanism design">mechanism design</a> theory". Myerson's contribu=
tions include the notion of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proper=
_equilibrium" title=3D"Proper equilibrium">proper equilibrium</a>, and an i=
mportant graduate text: <i>Game Theory, Analysis of Conflict</i>.<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-Myerson_1-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-Myerson-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Hurwicz introduced and=
 formalized the concept of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Incenti=
ve_compatibility" title=3D"Incentive compatibility">incentive compatibility=
</a>.
</p><p>In 2012, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alvin_E._Roth" tit=
le=3D"Alvin E. Roth">Alvin E. Roth</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Lloyd_Shapley" title=3D"Lloyd Shapley">Lloyd S. Shapley</a> were a=
warded the Nobel Prize in Economics "for the theory of stable allocations a=
nd the practice of market design". In 2014, the Nobel went to game theorist=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jean_Tirole" title=3D"Jean Tirole=
">Jean Tirole</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Different_types_of_games">D=
ifferent types of games</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"m=
w-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.=
php?title=3DGame_theory&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit se=
ction: Different types of games"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-edi=
tsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_games_in_game_th=
eory" title=3D"List of games in game theory">List of games in game theory</=
a></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Cooperative_/_non-cooperati=
ve"><span id=3D"Cooperative_.2F_non-cooperative"></span>Cooperative / non-c=
ooperative</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection=
-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DG=
ame_theory&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" title=3D"Edit section: Cooper=
ative / non-cooperative"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection=
-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main articles: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cooperative_game_th=
eory" title=3D"Cooperative game theory">Cooperative game theory</a> and <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Non-cooperative_game" class=3D"mw-red=
irect" title=3D"Non-cooperative game">Non-cooperative game</a></div>
<p>A game is <i>cooperative</i> if the players are able to form binding com=
mitments externally enforced (e.g. through <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Contract_law" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Contract law">contrac=
t law</a>). A game is <i>non-cooperative</i> if players cannot form allianc=
es or if all agreements need to be <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Self-enforcing_agreement" title=3D"Self-enforcing agreement">self-enforcin=
g</a> (e.g. through <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Credible_threa=
t" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Credible threat">credible threats</a>).<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-18" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Cooperative games are often analyzed through the framework of <i>coo=
perative game theory</i>, which focuses on predicting which coalitions will=
 form, the joint actions that groups take, and the resulting collective pay=
offs. It is different from <i>non-cooperative game theory</i> which focuses=
 on predicting individual players' actions and payoffs by analyzing <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nash_equilibria" class=3D"mw-redirect" ti=
tle=3D"Nash equilibria">Nash equilibria</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-19" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_no=
te-19"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-20" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-20"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>19<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Cooperative game theory provides a high-level approach as it describ=
es only the structure and payoffs of coalitions, whereas non-cooperative ga=
me theory also looks at how strategic interaction will affect the distribut=
ion of payoffs. As non-cooperative game theory is more general, cooperative=
 games can be analyzed through the approach of non-cooperative game theory =
(the converse does not hold) provided that sufficient assumptions are made =
to encompass all the possible strategies available to players due to the po=
ssibility of external enforcement of cooperation.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Symmetric_/_asymmetric"><sp=
an id=3D"Symmetric_.2F_asymmetric"></span>Symmetric / asymmetric</h3><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DGame_theory&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: Symmetric / asymmetric"><sp=
an>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></d=
iv>
<table id=3D"Payoff_matrix" style=3D"background:white; float: right; clear:=
