<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zero-sum_game" title=
=3D"Zero-sum game">Zero-sum game</a></div>
<p>Zero-sum games (more generally, constant-sum games) are games in which c=
hoices by players can neither increase nor decrease the available resources=
. In zero-sum games, the total benefit goes to all players in a game, for e=
very combination of strategies, and always adds to zero (more informally, a=
 player benefits only at the equal expense of others).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-2=
2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory=
#cite_note-22"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Poker" =
title=3D"Poker">Poker</a> exemplifies a zero-sum game (ignoring the possibi=
lity of the house's cut), because one wins exactly the amount one's opponen=
ts lose. Other zero-sum games include <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Matching_pennies" title=3D"Matching pennies">matching pennies</a> and m=
ost classical board games including <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Go_(board_game)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Go (board game)">Go</a> a=
nd <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chess" title=3D"Chess">chess</a=
>.
</p><p>Many games studied by game theorists (including the famed prisoner's=
 dilemma) are non-zero-sum games, because the <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Outcome_(game_theory)" title=3D"Outcome (game theory)">outcome<=
/a> has net results greater or less than zero. Informally, in non-zero-sum =
games, a gain by one player does not necessarily correspond with a loss by =
another.
</p><p>Furthermore, <i>constant-sum games</i> correspond to activities like=
 theft and gambling, but not to the fundamental economic situation in which=
 there are potential <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gains_from_tr=
ade" title=3D"Gains from trade">gains from trade</a>. It is possible to tra=
nsform any constant-sum game into a (possibly asymmetric) zero-sum game by =
adding a dummy player (often called "the board") whose losses compensate th=
e players' net winnings.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Simultaneous_/_sequential">=
<span id=3D"Simultaneous_.2F_sequential"></span>Simultaneous / sequential</=
h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[<=
/span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DGame_theory&a=
mp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" title=3D"Edit section: Simultaneous / seq=
uential"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</spa=
n></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main articles: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simultaneous_game" =
title=3D"Simultaneous game">Simultaneous game</a> and <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sequential_game" title=3D"Sequential game">Sequential g=
ame</a></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simultaneous_game" title=3D"Sim=
ultaneous game">Simultaneous games</a> are games where both players move si=
multaneously, or instead the later players are unaware of the earlier playe=
rs' actions (making them <i>effectively</i> simultaneous). <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sequential_game" title=3D"Sequential game">Sequent=
ial games</a> (a type of dynamic games) are games where players do not make=
 decisions simultaneously, and player's earlier actions affect the outcome =
and decisions of other players.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-23" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-23"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up> This need not be <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Perfect_infor=
mation" title=3D"Perfect information">perfect information</a> about every a=
ction of earlier players; it might be very little knowledge. For instance, =
a player may know that an earlier player did not perform one particular act=
ion, while they do not know which of the other available actions the first =
player actually performed.
</p><p>The difference between simultaneous and sequential games is captured=
 in the different representations discussed above. Often, <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Normal_form_game" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"No=
rmal form game">normal form</a> is used to represent simultaneous games, wh=
ile <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Extensive_form_game" class=3D"=
mw-redirect" title=3D"Extensive form game">extensive form</a> is used to re=
present sequential ones. The transformation of extensive to normal form is =
one way, meaning that multiple extensive form games correspond to the same =
normal form. Consequently, notions of equilibrium for simultaneous games ar=
e insufficient for reasoning about sequential games; see <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Subgame_perfection" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"S=
ubgame perfection">subgame perfection</a>.
</p><p>In short, the differences between sequential and simultaneous games =
are as follows:
</p>
