<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Perfect_information_and_imp=
erfect_information">Perfect information and imperfect information</h3><span=
 class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DGame_theory&amp;actio=
n=3Dedit&amp;section=3D9" title=3D"Edit section: Perfect information and im=
perfect information"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bra=
cket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Perfect_information"=
 title=3D"Perfect information">Perfect information</a></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:PD_with_outside_option.svg" c=
lass=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikip=
edia/commons/thumb/2/23/PD_with_outside_option.svg/330px-PD_with_outside_op=
tion.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"310" height=3D"141" class=3D"mw-f=
ile-element" data-file-width=3D"214" data-file-height=3D"97"></a><figcaptio=
n>A game of imperfect information. The dotted line represents ignorance on =
the part of player 2, formally called an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Information_set_(game_theory)" title=3D"Information set (game theory=
)">information set</a>.</figcaption></figure>
<p>An important subset of sequential games consists of games of perfect inf=
ormation. A game with perfect information means that all players, at every =
move in the game, know the previous history of the game and the moves previ=
ously made by all other players. An imperfect information game is played wh=
en the players do not know all moves already made by the opponent such as a=
 simultaneous move game.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:2_24-0" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-:2-24"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup> Examples of perfect-information games include <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Tic-tac-toe" title=3D"Tic-tac-toe">tic-tac-toe</a>, <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Draughts" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D=
"Draughts">checkers</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chess" ti=
tle=3D"Chess">chess</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Go_(b=
oard_game)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Go (board game)">Go</a>.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-25" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Game_theory#cite_note-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>24<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-26" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-26"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-27" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>26<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Many card games are games of imperfect information, such as <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Poker" title=3D"Poker">poker</a> and <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Contract_bridge" title=3D"Contract bri=
dge">bridge</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-28" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-28"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>27<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Perfect inf=
ormation is often confused with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Co=
mplete_information" title=3D"Complete information">complete information</a>=
, which is a similar concept pertaining to the common knowledge of each pla=
yer's sequence, strategies, and payoffs throughout gameplay.<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-29" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_=
theory#cite_note-29"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>28<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Complete information requires that every p=
layer know the strategies and payoffs available to the other players but no=
t necessarily the actions taken, whereas perfect information is knowledge o=
f all aspects of the game and players.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-30" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-30"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>29<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup> Games of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Information_as=
ymmetry" title=3D"Information asymmetry">incomplete information</a> can be =
reduced, however, to games of imperfect information by introducing "<a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Move_by_nature" title=3D"Move by nature">=
moves by nature</a>".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEShohamLeyton-Brown200860_3=
1-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theo=
ry#cite_note-FOOTNOTEShohamLeyton-Brown200860-31"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>30<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Bayesian_game">Bayesian gam=
e</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DGame_theor=
y&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D10" title=3D"Edit section: Bayesian game"=
><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span=
></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_game" title=
=3D"Bayesian game">Bayesian game</a></div>
<p>One of the assumptions of the Nash equilibrium is that every player has =
correct beliefs about the actions of the other players. However, there are =
many situations in game theory where participants do not fully understand t=
he characteristics of their opponents. Negotiators may be unaware of their =
opponent's valuation of the object of negotiation, companies may be unaware=
 of their opponent's cost functions, combatants may be unaware of their opp=
onent's strengths, and jurors may be unaware of their colleague's interpret=
ation of the evidence at trial. In some cases, participants may know the ch=
aracter of their opponent well, but may not know how well their opponent kn=
ows his or her own character.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-32" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-32"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>31<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_game" title=3D"Bay=
esian game">Bayesian game</a> means a strategic game with incomplete inform=
ation. For a strategic game, decision makers are players, and every player =
has a group of actions. A core part of the imperfect information specificat=
ion is the set of states. Every state completely describes a collection of =
characteristics relevant to the player such as their preferences and detail=
s about them. There must be a state for every set of features that some pla=
yer believes may exist.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-33" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-33"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>32<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:An_example_of_diagram.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-d=
escription"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thum=
b/8/8c/An_example_of_diagram.jpg/250px-An_example_of_diagram.jpg" decoding=
=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"133" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file=
-width=3D"1360" data-file-height=3D"726"></a><figcaption>Example of a Bayes=
ian game</figcaption></figure>
<p>For example, where Player 1 is unsure whether Player 2 would rather date=
 her or get away from her, while Player 2 understands Player 1's preference=
s as before. To be specific, supposing that Player 1 believes that Player 2=
 wants to date her under a probability of 1/2 and get away from her under a=
 probability of 1/2 (this evaluation comes from Player 1's experience proba=
bly: she faces players who want to date her half of the time in such a case=
 and players who want to avoid her half of the time). Due to the probabilit=
y involved, the analysis  of this situation requires to understand the play=
er's preference for the draw, even though people are only interested in pur=
e strategic equilibrium.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Combinatorial_games">Combin=
atorial games</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DGame_theory&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D11" title=3D"Edit section: C=
ombinatorial games"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Games in which the difficulty of finding an optimal strategy stems from =
the multiplicity of possible moves are called combinatorial games. Examples=
 include chess and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Go_(game)" titl=
e=3D"Go (game)">Go</a>. Games that involve <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Perfect_information" title=3D"Perfect information">imperfect infor=
mation</a> may also have a strong combinatorial character, for instance <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Backgammon" title=3D"Backgammon">back=
gammon</a>. There is no unified theory addressing combinatorial elements in=
 games. There are, however, mathematical tools that can solve some particul=
ar problems and answer some general questions.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Bewersdor=
ff2005_34-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/G=
ame_theory#cite_note-Bewersdorff2005-34"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>33<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Games of perfect information have been studied in <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Combinatorial_game_theory" title=3D"Combinatorial ga=
me theory">combinatorial game theory</a>, which has developed novel represe=
ntations, e.g. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Surreal_numbers" cl=
ass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Surreal numbers">surreal numbers</a>, as well =
as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Combinatorics" title=3D"Combina=
torics">combinatorial</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abst=
ract_algebra" title=3D"Abstract algebra">algebraic</a> (and <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Strategy_stealing_argument" class=3D"mw-redirect"=
 title=3D"Strategy stealing argument">sometimes non-constructive</a>) proof=
 methods to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Solved_game" title=3D"=
Solved game">solve games</a> of certain types, including "loopy" games that=
 may result in infinitely long sequences of moves. These methods address ga=
mes with higher combinatorial complexity than those usually considered in t=
raditional (or "economic") game theory.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-35" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-35">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>34<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-36" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-36"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>35<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> A typical game t=
hat has been solved this way is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/He=
x_(board_game)" title=3D"Hex (board game)">Hex</a>. A related field of stud=
y, drawing from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computational_comp=
lexity_theory" title=3D"Computational complexity theory">computational comp=
lexity theory</a>, is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_complex=
ity" title=3D"Game complexity">game complexity</a>, which is concerned with=
 estimating the computational difficulty of finding optimal strategies.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-37" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-37"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>36<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Research in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Artificial_inte=
lligence" title=3D"Artificial intelligence">artificial intelligence</a> has=
 addressed both perfect and imperfect information games that have very comp=
lex combinatorial structures (like chess, go, or backgammon) for which no p=
rovable optimal strategies have been found. The practical solutions involve=
 computational heuristics, like <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Al=
pha%E2%80%93beta_pruning" title=3D"Alpha=E2=80=93beta pruning">alpha=E2=80=
=93beta pruning</a> or use of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arti=
ficial_neural_network" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Artificial neural net=
work">artificial neural networks</a> trained by <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Reinforcement_learning" title=3D"Reinforcement learning">rein=
forcement learning</a>, which make games more tractable in computing practi=
ce.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Bewersdorff2005_34-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-Bewersdorff2005-34"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>33<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Jones2008_38-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-Jones2008-38"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>37<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Discrete_and_continuous_gam=
es">Discrete and continuous games</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/w/index.php?title=3DGame_theory&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D12" title=
=3D"Edit section: Discrete and continuous games"><span>edit</span></a><span=
 class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Much of game theory is concerned with finite, discrete games that have a=
 finite number of players, moves, events, outcomes, etc. Many concepts can =
be extended, however. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Continuous_g=
ame" title=3D"Continuous game">Continuous games</a> allow players to choose=
 a strategy from a continuous strategy set. For instance, <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cournot_competition" title=3D"Cournot competition">=
Cournot competition</a> is typically modeled with players' strategies being=
 any non-negative quantities, including fractional quantities.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Differential_games">Differe=
ntial games</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3D=
Game_theory&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D13" title=3D"Edit section: Diff=
erential games"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Differential_game" t=
itle=3D"Differential game">Differential game</a></div>
<p>Differential games such as the continuous <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Pursuit-evasion" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Pursuit-evasion"=
>pursuit and evasion game</a> are continuous games where the evolution of t=
he players' state variables is governed by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Differential_equation" title=3D"Differential equation">differentia=
l equations</a>. The problem of finding an optimal strategy in a differenti=
al game is closely related to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Optimal_control" title=3D"Optimal control">optimal control</a> theory. In p=
articular, there are two types of strategies: the open-loop strategies are =
found using the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pontryagin%27s_Min=
imum_Principle" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Pontryagin's Minimum Princip=
le">Pontryagin maximum principle</a> while the closed-loop strategies are f=
ound using <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hamilton%E2%80%93Jacobi=
%E2%80%93Bellman_equation" title=3D"Hamilton=E2=80=93Jacobi=E2=80=93Bellman=
 equation">Bellman's Dynamic Programming</a> method.
</p><p>A particular case of differential games are the games with a random =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Time_horizon" title=3D"Time horizo=
n">time horizon</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-PM66_39-0" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-PM66-39"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>38<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup> In such games, the terminal time is a random variable with a given <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability_distribution" title=3D"Pr=
obability distribution">probability distribution</a> function. Therefore, t=
he players maximize the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematic=
al_expectation" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Mathematical expectation">ma=
thematical expectation</a> of the cost function. It was shown that the modi=
fied optimization problem can be reformulated as a discounted differential =
game over an infinite time interval.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Evolutionary_game_theory">E=
volutionary game theory</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"m=
w-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.=
php?title=3DGame_theory&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D14" title=3D"Edit s=
ection: Evolutionary game theory"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Evolutionary_game_th=
eory" title=3D"Evolutionary game theory">Evolutionary game theory</a></div>
<p>Evolutionary game theory studies players who adjust their strategies ove=
r time according to rules that are not necessarily rational or farsighted.<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-Newton2018renaissance_40-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-Newton2018renaissan=
ce-40"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>39<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup>  In general, the evolution of strategies over time accor=
ding to such rules is modeled as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Markov_chain" title=3D"Markov chain">Markov chain</a> with a state variabl=
e such as the current strategy profile or how the game has been played in t=
he recent past. Such rules may feature imitation, optimization, or survival=
 of the fittest.
</p><p>In biology, such models can represent <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Evolution" title=3D"Evolution">evolution</a>, in which offspring=
 adopt their parents' strategies and parents who play more successful strat=
egies (i.e. corresponding to higher payoffs) have a greater number of offsp=
ring. In the social sciences, such models typically represent strategic adj=
ustment by players who play a game many times within their lifetime and, co=
nsciously or unconsciously, occasionally adjust their strategies.<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEWebb2007_41-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-FOOTNOTEWebb2007-41"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>40<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Stochastic_outcomes_(and_re=
lation_to_other_fields)"><span id=3D"Stochastic_outcomes_.28and_relation_to=
_other_fields.29"></span>Stochastic outcomes (and relation to other fields)=
</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">=
[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DGame_theory=
&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D15" title=3D"Edit section: Stochastic outc=
omes (and relation to other fields)"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw=
-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Individual decision problems with stochastic outcomes are sometimes cons=
idered "one-player games". They may be modeled using similar tools within t=
he related disciplines of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decision=
_theory" title=3D"Decision theory">decision theory</a>, <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Operations_research" title=3D"Operations research">op=
erations research</a>, and areas of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Artificial_intelligence" title=3D"Artificial intelligence">artificial int=
elligence</a>, particularly <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AI_pla=
nning" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"AI planning">AI planning</a> (with un=
certainty) and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multi-agent_system"=
 title=3D"Multi-agent system">multi-agent system</a>. Although these fields=
 may have different motivators, the mathematics involved are substantially =
the same, e.g. using <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Markov_decisi=
on_process" title=3D"Markov decision process">Markov decision processes</a>=
 (MDP).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-42" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-42"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>41<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Stochastic outcomes can also be modeled in terms of game theory by a=
dding a randomly acting player who makes "chance moves" ("<a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Move_by_nature" title=3D"Move by nature">moves by n=
ature</a>").<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEOsborneRubinstein1994_43-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_no=
te-FOOTNOTEOsborneRubinstein1994-43"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4=
2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This player is not typical=
ly considered a third player in what is otherwise a two-player game, but me=
rely serves to provide a roll of the dice where required by the game.
</p><p>For some problems, different approaches to modeling stochastic outco=
mes may lead to different solutions. For example, the difference in approac=
h between MDPs and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minimax" ti=
tle=3D"Minimax">minimax solution</a> is that the latter considers the worst=
-case over a set of adversarial moves, rather than reasoning in expectation=
 about these moves given a fixed probability distribution. The minimax appr=
oach may be advantageous where stochastic models of uncertainty are not ava=
ilable, but may also be overestimating extremely unlikely (but costly) even=
ts, dramatically swaying the strategy in such scenarios if it is assumed th=
at an adversary can force such an event to happen.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-McMah=
an_44-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_=
theory#cite_note-McMahan-44"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>43<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> (See <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Black_swan_theory" title=3D"Black swan theory">Black swan theor=
y</a> for more discussion on this kind of modeling issue, particularly as i=
t relates to predicting and limiting losses in investment banking.)
</p><p>General models that include all elements of stochastic outcomes, adv=
ersaries, and partial or noisy observability (of moves by other players) ha=
ve also been studied. The "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gold_st=
andard" title=3D"Gold standard">gold standard</a>" is considered to be part=
ially observable <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stochastic_game" =
title=3D"Stochastic game">stochastic game</a> (POSG), but few realistic pro=
blems are computationally feasible in POSG representation.<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-McMahan_44-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Game_theory#cite_note-McMahan-44"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4=
3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Metagames">Metagames</h3><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DGame_theory&amp;ac=
tion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D16" title=3D"Edit section: Metagames"><span>edit<=
/span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>These are games the play of which is the development of the rules for an=
other game, the target or subject game. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Metagame" title=3D"Metagame">Metagames</a> seek to maximize the utili=
ty value of the rule set developed. The theory of metagames is related to <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mechanism_design" title=3D"Mechanis=
m design">mechanism design</a> theory.
</p><p>The term <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metagame_analysis"=
 title=3D"Metagame analysis">metagame analysis</a> is also used to refer to=
 a practical approach developed by Nigel Howard,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOT=
EHoward1971_45-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Game_theory#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHoward1971-45"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>44<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> whereby a situ=
ation is framed as a strategic game in which stakeholders try to realize th=
eir objectives by means of the options available to them. Subsequent develo=
pments have led to the formulation of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Confrontation_analysis" title=3D"Confrontation analysis">confrontation =
analysis</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Mean_field_game_theory">Mea=
n field game theory</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?=
title=3DGame_theory&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D17" title=3D"Edit secti=
on: Mean field game theory"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mean_field_game_theo=
ry" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Mean field game theory">Mean field game =
theory</a></div>
<p>Mean field game theory is the study of strategic decision making in very=
 large populations of small interacting agents. This class of problems was =
considered in the economics literature by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Boyan_Jovanovic" title=3D"Boyan Jovanovic">Boyan Jovanovic</a> and =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_W._Rosenthal" title=3D"Robe=
rt W. Rosenthal">Robert W. Rosenthal</a>, in the engineering literature by =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peter_E._Caines" title=3D"Peter E.=
 Caines">Peter E. Caines</a>, and by mathematicians <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Pierre-Louis_Lions" title=3D"Pierre-Louis Lions">Pierre-L=
ouis Lions</a> and Jean-Michel Lasry.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Representation_of_games">Re=
presentation of games</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.ph=
p?title=3DGame_theory&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D18" title=3D"Edit sec=
tion: Representation of games"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-edits=
ection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The games studied in game theory are well-defined mathematical objects. =
To be fully defined, a game must specify the following elements: the <i>pla=
yers</i> of the game, the <i>information</i> and <i>actions</i> available t=
o each player at each decision point, and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Utility" title=3D"Utility"><i>payoffs</i></a> for each outcome.=
 (Eric Rasmusen refers to these four "essential elements" by the acronym "P=
API".)<sup id=3D"cite_ref-r7a_46-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-r7a-46"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>45<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-r7b_47-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Game_theory#cite_note-r7b-47"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>46<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-r7c_48-0" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#ci=
te_note-r7c-48"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>47<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-r7d_49-0" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-r7d-49"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>48<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup> A game theorist typically uses these elements, along with a <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Solution_concept" title=3D"Solution con=
cept">solution concept</a> of their choosing, to deduce a set of equilibriu=
m <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Strategy_(game_theory)" title=3D=
"Strategy (game theory)">strategies</a> for each player such that, when the=
se strategies are employed, no player can profit by unilaterally deviating =
from their strategy. These equilibrium strategies determine an <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Economic_equilibrium" title=3D"Economic equili=
brium">equilibrium</a> to the game=E2=80=94a stable state in which either o=
ne outcome occurs or a set of outcomes occur with known probability.
</p><p>Most cooperative games are presented in the characteristic function =
form, while the extensive and the normal forms are used to define noncooper=
ative games.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Extensive_form">Extensive f=
orm</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DGame_the=
ory&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D19" title=3D"Edit section: Extensive fo=
rm"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></s=
pan></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Extensive_form_game"=
 class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Extensive form game">Extensive form game</a=
></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Ultimatum_Game_Extensive_Form=
.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.or=
g/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/be/Ultimatum_Game_Extensive_Form.svg/250px-Ulti=
matum_Game_Extensive_Form.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=
=3D"125" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"148" data-file-height=
=3D"74"></a><figcaption>An extensive form game</figcaption></figure>
<p>The extensive form can be used to formalize games with a time sequencing=
 of moves. Extensive form games can be visualized using game <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tree_(graph_theory)" title=3D"Tree (graph theory=
)">trees</a> (as pictured here). Here each <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Graph_(discrete_mathematics)" title=3D"Graph (discrete mathematics=
)">vertex</a> (or node) represents a point of choice for a player. The play=
er is specified by a number listed by the vertex. The lines out of the vert=
ex represent a possible action for that player. The payoffs are specified a=
t the bottom of the tree. The extensive form can be viewed as a multi-playe=
r generalization of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decision_tre=
e" title=3D"Decision tree">decision tree</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-50" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_no=
te-50"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>49<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup> To solve any extensive form game, <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Backward_induction" title=3D"Backward induction">backwar=
d induction</a> must be used. It involves working backward up the game tree=
 to determine what a rational player would do at the last vertex of the tre=
e, what the player with the previous move would do given that the player wi=
th the last move is rational, and so on until the first vertex of the tree =
is reached.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-51" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-51"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>50<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The game pictured consists of two players.  The way this particular =
game is structured (i.e., with sequential decision making and perfect infor=
mation), <i>Player 1</i> "moves" first by choosing either <var style=3D"pad=
ding-right: 1px;">F</var> or <var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">U</var> (fa=
ir or unfair). Next in the sequence, <i>Player 2</i>, who has now observed =
<i>Player 1</i><span class=3D"nowrap" style=3D"padding-left:0.1em;">'</span=
>s move, can choose to play either <var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">A</va=
r> or <var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">R</var>  (accept or reject). Once =
<i>Player 2</i> has made their choice, the game is considered finished and =
each player gets their respective payoff, represented in the image as two n=
umbers, where the first number represents Player 1's payoff, and the second=
 number represents Player 2's payoff.  Suppose that <i>Player 1</i> chooses=
 <var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">U</var> and then <i>Player 2</i> choose=
s <var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">A</var>: <i>Player 1</i> then gets a p=
ayoff of "eight" (which in real-world terms can be interpreted in many ways=
, the simplest of which is in terms of money but could mean things such as =
eight days of vacation or eight countries conquered or even eight more oppo=
rtunities to play the same game against other players) and <i>Player 2</i> =
gets a payoff of "two".
</p><p>The extensive form can also capture simultaneous-move games and game=
s with imperfect information. To represent it, either a dotted line connect=
s different vertices to represent them as being part of the same informatio=
n set (i.e. the players do not know at which point they are), or a closed l=
ine is drawn around them. (See example in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Game_theory#Perfect_information_and_imperfect_information">impe=
rfect information section</a>.)
</p>
