<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"General_and_applied_uses">G=
eneral and applied uses</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"m=
w-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.=
php?title=3DGame_theory&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D23" title=3D"Edit s=
ection: General and applied uses"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>As a method of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Applied_mathemat=
ics" title=3D"Applied mathematics">applied mathematics</a>, game theory has=
 been used to study a wide variety of human and animal behaviors. It was in=
itially developed in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Economics" ti=
tle=3D"Economics">economics</a> to understand a large collection of economi=
c behaviors, including behaviors of firms, markets, and consumers. The firs=
t use of game-theoretic analysis was by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Antoine_Augustin_Cournot" title=3D"Antoine Augustin Cournot">Antoine =
Augustin Cournot</a> in 1838 with his solution of the <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cournot_competition" title=3D"Cournot competition">Cour=
not duopoly</a>. The use of game theory in the social sciences has expanded=
, and game theory has been applied to political, sociological, and psycholo=
gical behaviors as well.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Larson_70-0" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-Larson-70"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>69<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup>
</p><p>Although pre-twentieth-century <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Natural_history" title=3D"Natural history">naturalists</a> such as <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_Darwin" title=3D"Charles Darwi=
n">Charles Darwin</a> made game-theoretic kinds of statements, the use of g=
ame-theoretic analysis in biology began with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Ronald_Fisher" title=3D"Ronald Fisher">Ronald Fisher</a>'s studi=
es of animal behavior during the 1930s. This work predates the name "game t=
heory", but it shares many important features with this field. The developm=
ents in economics were later applied to biology largely by John Maynard Smi=
th in his 1982 book <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Evolution_a=
nd_the_Theory_of_Games" title=3D"Evolution and the Theory of Games">Evoluti=
on and the Theory of Games</a></i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-71" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-71"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>70<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup>
</p><p>In addition to being used to describe, predict, and explain behavior=
, game theory has also been used to develop theories of ethical or normativ=
e behavior and to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decision_theory#=
Normative_and_descriptive_decision_theory" title=3D"Decision theory">prescr=
ibe</a> such behavior.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Camerer2003_72-0" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-Camerer=
2003-72"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>71<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup> In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Economics_=
and_philosophy" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Economics and philosophy">ec=
onomics and philosophy</a>, scholars have applied game theory to help in th=
e understanding of good or proper behavior. Game-theoretic approaches have =
also been suggested in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philoso=
phy_of_language" title=3D"Philosophy of language">philosophy of language</a=
> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philosophy_of_science" title=
=3D"Philosophy of science">philosophy of science</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-73=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#=
cite_note-73"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>72<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup> Game-theoretic arguments of this type can be foun=
d as far back as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plato" title=3D"P=
lato">Plato</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-74" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-74"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>73<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> An alternat=
ive version of game theory, called chemical game theory, represents the pla=
yer's choices as metaphorical chemical reactant molecules called "knowlecul=
es".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-75" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-75"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>74<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> &nbsp;Chemical game the=
ory then calculates the outcomes as equilibrium solutions to a system of ch=
emical reactions.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Description_and_modeling">D=
escription and modeling</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"m=
w-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.=
php?title=3DGame_theory&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D24" title=3D"Edit s=
ection: Description and modeling"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Centipede_game.svg" class=3D"=
mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/com=
mons/thumb/9/96/Centipede_game.svg/330px-Centipede_game.svg.png" decoding=
=3D"async" width=3D"310" height=3D"103" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file=
-width=3D"2496" data-file-height=3D"832"></a><figcaption>A four-stage <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Centipede_game" title=3D"Centipede game=
">centipede game</a></figcaption></figure>
<p>The primary use of game theory is to describe and <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Conceptual_model#Economic_models" title=3D"Conceptual mo=
del">model</a> how human populations behave.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Te=
mplate Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citatio=
n needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (=
November 2019)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup> Some<sup class=3D"nop=
rint Inline-Template" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Words_to_watch#Unsupported_=
attributions" title=3D"Wikipedia:Manual of Style/Words to watch"><span titl=
e=3D"The material near this tag possibly uses too-vague attribution or weas=
el words. (July 2012)">who?</span></a></i>]</sup> scholars believe that by =
finding the equilibria of games they can predict how actual human populatio=
ns will behave when confronted with situations analogous to the game being =
studied. This particular view of game theory has been criticized. It is arg=
ued that the assumptions made by game theorists are often violated when app=
lied to real-world situations. Game theorists usually assume players act ra=
tionally, but in practice, human rationality and/or behavior often deviates=
 from the model of rationality as used in game theory. Game theorists respo=
nd by comparing their assumptions to those used in <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Physics" title=3D"Physics">physics</a>. Thus while their a=
ssumptions do not always hold, they can treat game theory as a reasonable s=
cientific <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Idealization_(science_ph=
ilosophy)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Idealization (science philosophy)=
">ideal</a> akin to the models used by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Physicist" title=3D"Physicist">physicists</a>. However, empirical work=
 has shown that in some classic games, such as the <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Centipede_game" title=3D"Centipede game">centipede game</a=
>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Guess_2/3_of_the_average" title=
=3D"Guess 2/3 of the average">guess 2/3 of the average</a> game, and the <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dictator_game" title=3D"Dictator gam=
e">dictator game</a>, people regularly do not play Nash equilibria. There i=
s an ongoing debate regarding the importance of these experiments and wheth=
er the analysis of the experiments fully captures all aspects of the releva=
nt situation.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-77" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-77"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>b<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Some game theorists, following the work of John Maynard Smith and <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_R._Price" title=3D"George R. =
Price">George R. Price</a>, have turned to evolutionary game theory in orde=
r to resolve these issues. These models presume either no rationality or <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bounded_rationality" title=3D"Bounde=
d rationality">bounded rationality</a> on the part of players. Despite the =
name, evolutionary game theory does not necessarily presume <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Natural_selection" title=3D"Natural selection">na=
tural selection</a> in the biological sense. Evolutionary game theory inclu=
des both biological as well as cultural evolution and also models of indivi=
dual learning (for example, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fictit=
ious_play" title=3D"Fictitious play">fictitious play</a> dynamics).
</p>
