<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Evolutionary_game_th=
eory" title=3D"Evolutionary game theory">Evolutionary game theory</a></div>
<p>Unlike those in economics, the payoffs for games in <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biology" title=3D"Biology">biology</a> are often inter=
preted as corresponding to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fitness=
_(biology)" title=3D"Fitness (biology)">fitness</a>. In addition, the focus=
 has been less on equilibria that correspond to a notion of rationality and=
 more on ones that would be maintained by evolutionary forces. The best-kno=
wn equilibrium in biology is known as the <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Evolutionarily_stable_strategy" title=3D"Evolutionarily stable s=
trategy">evolutionarily stable strategy</a></i> (ESS), first introduced in =
(<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#CITEREFMaynard_SmithP=
rice1973">Maynard Smith &amp; Price 1973</a>). Although its initial motivat=
ion did not involve any of the mental requirements of the Nash equilibrium,=
 every ESS is a Nash equilibrium.
</p><p>In biology, game theory has been used as a model to understand many =
different phenomena. It was first used to explain the evolution (and stabil=
ity) of the approximate 1:1 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sex_ra=
tio" title=3D"Sex ratio">sex ratios</a>. (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Game_theory#CITEREFFisher1930">Fisher 1930</a>) suggested that the =
1:1 sex ratios are a result of evolutionary forces acting on individuals wh=
o could be seen as trying to maximize their number of grandchildren.
</p><p>Additionally, biologists have used evolutionary game theory and the =
ESS to explain the emergence of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/An=
imal_communication" title=3D"Animal communication">animal communication</a>=
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHarperMaynard_Smith2003_125-0" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-FOOTNOT=
EHarperMaynard_Smith2003-125"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>122<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The analysis of <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Signaling_games" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Si=
gnaling games">signaling games</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Cheap_talk" title=3D"Cheap talk">other communication games</a> has pro=
vided insight into the evolution of communication among animals. For exampl=
e, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mobbing_behavior" class=3D"=
mw-redirect" title=3D"Mobbing behavior">mobbing behavior</a> of many specie=
s, in which a large number of prey animals attack a larger predator, seems =
to be an example of spontaneous emergent organization. Ants have also been =
shown to exhibit feed-forward behavior akin to fashion (see <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Ormerod" title=3D"Paul Ormerod">Paul Ormerod=
</a>'s <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Butterfly_Economics" tit=
le=3D"Butterfly Economics">Butterfly Economics</a></i>).
</p><p>Biologists have used the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ch=
icken_(game)" title=3D"Chicken (game)">game of chicken</a> to analyze fight=
ing behavior and territoriality.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-126" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-126"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>123<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup>
</p><p>According to Maynard Smith, in the preface to <i>Evolution and the T=
heory of Games</i>, "paradoxically, it has turned out that game theory is m=
ore readily applied to biology than to the field of economic behaviour for =
which it was originally designed". Evolutionary game theory has been used t=
o explain many seemingly incongruous phenomena in nature.<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-stan-egt_127-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Game_theory#cite_note-stan-egt-127"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>124<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>One such phenomenon is known as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Altruism_in_animals" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Altruism in animal=
s">biological altruism</a>. This is a situation in which an organism appear=
s to act in a way that benefits other organisms and is detrimental to itsel=
f. This is distinct from traditional notions of altruism because such actio=
ns are not conscious, but appear to be evolutionary adaptations to increase=
 overall fitness. Examples can be found in species ranging from vampire bat=
s that regurgitate blood they have obtained from a night's hunting and give=
 it to group members who have failed to feed, to worker bees that care for =
the queen bee for their entire lives and never mate, to <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vervet_monkey" title=3D"Vervet monkey">vervet monkeys=
</a> that warn group members of a predator's approach, even when it endange=
rs that individual's chance of survival.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-qudzyh_128-0" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cit=
e_note-qudzyh-128"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>125<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> All of these actions increase the overall f=
itness of a group, but occur at a cost to the individual.
</p><p>Evolutionary game theory explains this altruism with the idea of <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kin_selection" title=3D"Kin selection=
">kin selection</a>. Altruists discriminate between the individuals they he=
lp and favor relatives. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kin_select=
ion#Hamilton's_rule" title=3D"Kin selection">Hamilton's rule</a> explains t=
he evolutionary rationale behind this selection with the equation <span cla=
ss=3D"texhtml">c &lt; b =C3=97 r</span>, where the cost <var class=3D"var-s=
erif">c</var> to the altruist must be less than the benefit <link rel=3D"mw=
-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1003227249"><va=
r class=3D"var-serif">b</var> to the recipient multiplied by the coefficien=
t of relatedness <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data=
:TemplateStyles:r1003227249"><var class=3D"var-serif">r</var>. The more clo=
sely related two organisms are causes the incidences of altruism to increas=
e because they share many of the same alleles. This means that the altruist=
ic individual, by ensuring that the alleles of its close relative are passe=
d on through survival of its offspring, can forgo the option of having offs=
pring itself because the same number of alleles are passed on. For example,=
 helping a sibling (in diploid animals) has a coefficient of <span class=3D=
"frac"><span class=3D"num">1</span>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"den">2</span></s=
pan>, because (on average) an individual shares half of the alleles in its =
sibling's offspring. Ensuring that enough of a sibling's offspring survive =
to adulthood precludes the necessity of the altruistic individual producing=
 offspring.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-qudzyh_128-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-qudzyh-128"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>125<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p> The coefficient values depend heavily on the scope of the playing field;=
 for example if the choice of whom to favor includes all genetic living thi=
ngs, not just all relatives, we assume the discrepancy between all humans o=
nly accounts for approximately 1% of the diversity in the playing field, a =
coefficient that was <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-=
data:TemplateStyles:r1154941027"><span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"num">1=
</span>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"den">2</span></span> in the smaller field be=
comes 0.995. Similarly if it is considered that information other than that=
 of a genetic nature (e.g. epigenetics, religion, science, etc.) persisted =
through time the playing field becomes larger still, and the discrepancies =
smaller.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Computer_science_and_logic"=
>Computer science and logic</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/i=
ndex.php?title=3DGame_theory&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D33" title=3D"E=
dit section: Computer science and logic"><span>edit</span></a><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Game theory has come to play an increasingly important role in <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logic" title=3D"Logic">logic</a> and in <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_science" title=3D"Computer=
 science">computer science</a>. Several logical theories have a basis in <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_semantics" title=3D"Game semant=
ics">game semantics</a>. In addition, computer scientists have used games t=
o model <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Interactive_computation" t=
itle=3D"Interactive computation">interactive computations</a>. Also, game t=
heory provides a theoretical basis to the field of <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Multi-agent_system" title=3D"Multi-agent system">multi-age=
nt systems</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-ShohamLeyton-Brown2008_129-0" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-Sh=
ohamLeyton-Brown2008-129"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>126<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Separately, game theory has played a role in <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Online_algorithm" title=3D"Online algorithm">online algor=
ithms</a>; in particular, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/K-se=
rver_problem" title=3D"K-server problem"><var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;"=
>k</var>-server problem</a>, which has in the past been referred to as <i>g=
ames with moving costs</i> and <i>request-answer games</i>.<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-FOOTNOTEBen-DavidBorodinKarpTardos1994_130-0" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBen-David=
BorodinKarpTardos1994-130"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>127<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Yao%27s_principle" title=3D"Yao's principle">Yao's principle</a> is a=
 game-theoretic technique for proving <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Upper_and_lower_bounds" title=3D"Upper and lower bounds">lower bounds</=
a> on the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analysis_of_algorithms" =
title=3D"Analysis of algorithms">computational complexity</a> of <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Randomized_algorithm" title=3D"Randomized al=
gorithm">randomized algorithms</a>, especially online algorithms.
</p><p>The emergence of the Internet has motivated the development of algor=
ithms for finding equilibria in games, markets, computational auctions, pee=
r-to-peer systems, and security and information markets. <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algorithmic_game_theory" title=3D"Algorithmic game t=
heory">Algorithmic game theory</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-nisan2007_90-1" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_no=
te-nisan2007-90"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>87<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and within it <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Algorithmic_mechanism_design" title=3D"Algorithmic mechanism desig=
n">algorithmic mechanism design</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-nisanronen2001_89-1"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#c=
ite_note-nisanronen2001-89"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>86<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> combine computational <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algorithm_design" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Algorithm design">algorithm design</a> and analysis of <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_system" title=3D"Complex system">complex s=
ystems</a> with economic theory.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-131" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-131"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>128<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-132" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-132"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>129<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-133" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_th=
eory#cite_note-133"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>130<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Game theory has multiple applications in the field of artificial int=
elligence and machine learning. It is often used in developing autonomous s=
ystems that can make complex decisions in uncertain environment.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-134" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Game_theory#cite_note-134"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>131<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Some other areas of application of =
game theory in AI/ML context are as follows - multi-agent system formation,=
 reinforcement learning,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-135" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-135"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>132<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> mechanism design etc.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-136" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-136"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>133<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> B=
y using game theory to model the behavior of other agents and anticipate th=
eir actions, AI/ML systems can make better decisions and operate more effec=
tively.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-137" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-137"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>134<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Philosophy">Philosophy</h3>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DGame_theory&amp;=
action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D34" title=3D"Edit section: Philosophy"><span>ed=
it</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
