<td style=3D"font-size: 90%;" colspan=3D"3"><i>Stag hunt</i>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
<p>Game theory has been put to several uses in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Philosophy" title=3D"Philosophy">philosophy</a>. Responding to=
 two papers by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Willard_Van_Orman_Q=
uine" title=3D"Willard Van Orman Quine">W.V.O. Quine</a>&nbsp;(<a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#CITEREFQuine1960">1960</a>, <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#CITEREFQuine1967">1967</a>),=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#CITEREFLewis1969">Lew=
is (1969)</a> used game theory to develop a philosophical account of <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Convention_(norm)" title=3D"Convention (=
norm)">convention</a>. In so doing, he provided the first analysis of <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Common_knowledge_(logic)" title=3D"Comm=
on knowledge (logic)">common knowledge</a> and employed it in analyzing pla=
y in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coordination_game" title=3D"C=
oordination game">coordination games</a>. In addition, he first suggested t=
hat one can understand <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meaning_(se=
miotics)" title=3D"Meaning (semiotics)">meaning</a> in terms of <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Signaling_games" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Signaling games">signaling games</a>. This later suggestion has been pu=
rsued by several philosophers since Lewis.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-138" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-=
138"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>135<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEGrimKokalisAlai-TaftiKilb2004_=
139-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_th=
eory#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGrimKokalisAlai-TaftiKilb2004-139"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>136<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Foll=
owing <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#CITEREFLewis1969=
">Lewis (1969)</a> game-theoretic account of conventions, <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edna_Ullmann-Margalit" title=3D"Edna Ullmann-Margal=
it">Edna Ullmann-Margalit</a> (1977) and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Cristina_Bicchieri" title=3D"Cristina Bicchieri">Bicchieri</a> (2006=
) have developed theories of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Socia=
l_norms" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Social norms">social norms</a> that=
 define them as Nash equilibria that result from transforming a mixed-motiv=
e game into a coordination game.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-140" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-140"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>137<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-141" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-141"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>138<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Game theory has also challenged philosophers to think in terms of in=
teractive <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Epistemology" title=3D"E=
pistemology">epistemology</a>: what it means for a collective to have commo=
n beliefs or knowledge, and what are the consequences of this knowledge for=
 the social outcomes resulting from the interactions of agents. Philosopher=
s who have worked in this area include Bicchieri (1989, 1993),<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-142" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ga=
me_theory#cite_note-142"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>139<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-143" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-143">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>140<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brian_Skyrms" title=
=3D"Brian Skyrms">Skyrms</a> (1990),<sup id=3D"cite_ref-144" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-144"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>141<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_Stalnaker" =
title=3D"Robert Stalnaker">Stalnaker</a> (1999).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-145" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite=
_note-145"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>142<span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The synthesis of game theory with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Ethics" title=3D"Ethics">ethics</a> was championed by <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/R._B._Braithwaite" title=3D"R. B. Braithwaite">R=
. B. Braithwaite</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-146" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-146"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>143<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> T=
he hope was that rigorous mathematical analysis of game theory might help f=
ormalize the more imprecise philosophical discussions. However, this expect=
ation was only materialized to a limited extent.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-147" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite=
_note-147"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>144<span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ethics" title=3D"Ethics"=
>ethics</a>, some (most notably David Gauthier, Gregory Kavka, and Jean Ham=
pton) <sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">=
[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Word=
s_to_watch#Unsupported_attributions" title=3D"Wikipedia:Manual of Style/Wor=
ds to watch"><span title=3D"The material near this tag possibly uses too-va=
gue attribution or weasel words. (July 2012)">who?</span></a></i>]</sup> au=
thors have attempted to pursue <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tho=
mas_Hobbes" title=3D"Thomas Hobbes">Thomas Hobbes</a>' project of deriving =
morality from self-interest. Since games like the <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Prisoner%27s_dilemma" title=3D"Prisoner's dilemma">prisoner=
's dilemma</a> present an apparent conflict between morality and self-inter=
est, explaining why cooperation is required by self-interest is an importan=
t component of this project. This general strategy is a component of the ge=
neral <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Social_contract" title=3D"So=
cial contract">social contract</a> view in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Political_philosophy" title=3D"Political philosophy">political phi=
losophy</a> (for examples, see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gam=
e_theory#CITEREFGauthier1986">Gauthier (1986)</a> and <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#CITEREFKavka1986">Kavka (1986)</a>).<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-148" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Game_theory#cite_note-148"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>d<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Other authors have attempted to use evolutionary game theory in orde=
r to explain the emergence of human attitudes about morality and correspond=
ing animal behaviors. These authors look at several games including the pri=
soner's dilemma, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stag_hunt" title=
=3D"Stag hunt">stag hunt</a>, and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Nash_bargaining_game" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Nash bargaining ga=
me">Nash bargaining game</a> as providing an explanation for the emergence =
of attitudes about morality (see, e.g., Skyrms&nbsp;(<a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#CITEREFSkyrms1996">1996</a>, <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#CITEREFSkyrms2004">2004</a>) and Sobe=
r and Wilson&nbsp;(<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#CIT=
EREFSoberWilson1998">1998</a>)).
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Epidemiology">Epidemiology<=
/h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DGame_theory&=
amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D35" title=3D"Edit section: Epidemiology"><s=
pan>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></=
div>
<p>Since the decision to take a vaccine for a particular disease is often m=
ade by individuals, who may consider a range of factors and parameters in m=
aking this decision (such as the incidence and prevalence of the disease, p=
erceived and real risks associated with contracting the disease,  mortality=
 rate, perceived and real risks associated with vaccination, and financial =
cost of vaccination), game theory has been used to model and predict vaccin=
ation uptake in a society.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-149" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-149"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>145<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
><sup id=3D"cite_ref-150" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Game_theory#cite_note-150"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>146<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
